  "prompt": "Who are the prosecution and how does a witness help them in court?",
  "response": "In a legal context:\n\nProsecution:\n- The party responsible for bringing criminal charges against a defendant\n- Typically represented by government attorneys like district attorneys or state prosecutors\n- Their role is to prove the defendant's guilt beyond a reasonable doubt\n- They present evidence and arguments to show the defendant committed the alleged crime\n\nWitnesses help the prosecution by:\n1. Providing direct testimony about events related to the case\n2. Offering eyewitness accounts of what occurred\n3. Presenting expert testimony to explain technical or scientific aspects\n4. Corroborating other evidence\n5. Helping establish the sequence of events\n6. Supporting the prosecution's legal arguments\n7. Potentially identifying the defendant or describing the crime\n8. Providing credible, firsthand information about the alleged criminal act\n\nThe goal of prosecution witnesses is to provide compelling, truthful information that supports the criminal charges and helps prove the defendant's guilt.",
